replies.bodyText:
🤔 I'm fine with the name, I have more concern with the need of this annotation: I'm worried that sooner or later this problem (circular dependencies) will appear again if we continue to use construction injection.
What if we generate the constructor with all the parameters (to allow manual instantiation) but then we inject on fields? Does it solve the need to have lazy init?
@evacchi wdyt? If this works I would prefer to do this change instead of have the risk to add Lazy annotation "everywhere"

ok, here's what I think

I don't love the "Annotator" at all really :P I believe that we should actually move to templates everywhere.
We don't necessarily have to introduce templates with this PR but then I would at least wish for a follow-up JIRA where we try; I am trying to do it for Rules -- the code there is arguably less, though
However, the following code could be substituted for the injection of Instance/Collection
(and in fact IIRC we were injecting a collection, before)

    @javax.inject.Inject()
    public TravellersProcess(org.kie.kogito.app.Application app, org.kie.kogito.handlers.GreetingTravellerService_greetTraveller_3_Handler greetingTravellerService_greetTraveller_3_Handler, org.kie.kogito.handlers.TravellerAuditService_auditTraveller_7_Handler travellerAuditService_auditTraveller_7_Handler, org.kie.kogito.handlers.StoreTravellerService_storeTraveller_2_Handler storeTravellerService_storeTraveller_2_Handler) {
        super(app.config().process());
        this.app = app;
        org.kie.api.runtime.process.WorkItemManager workItemManager = services.getWorkItemManager();
        workItemManager.registerWorkItemHandler("org.acme.travels.services.GreetingTravellerService_greetTraveller_3_Handler", greetingTravellerService_greetTraveller_3_Handler);
        workItemManager.registerWorkItemHandler("org.acme.travels.services.TravellerAuditService_auditTraveller_7_Handler", travellerAuditService_auditTraveller_7_Handler);
        workItemManager.registerWorkItemHandler("org.acme.travels.services.StoreTravellerService_storeTraveller_2_Handler", storeTravellerService_storeTraveller_2_Handler);
        this.activate();
    }
in other words:
    @javax.inject.Inject()
    public TravellersProcess(
        org.kie.kogito.app.Application app, 
        // java.util.Collection in the case of Spring
        javax.enterprise.inject.Instance<org.kie.api.runtime.process.WorkItemHandler> handlers) {
        super(app.config().process());
        this.app = app;
        org.kie.api.runtime.process.WorkItemManager workItemManager = services.getWorkItemManager();
        for (WorkItemHandler wih : handlers) {
            workItemManager.registerWorkItemHandler(wih.getClass().getCanonicalName(), wih);
        }
        this.activate();
    }
to the point where we can actually move the logic to a super constructor:
protected AbstractProcess(
    org.kie.kogito.app.Application app, 
    // iterable is a common superclass between Instance (CDI) and Collection (Spring)
    Iterable<org.kie.api.runtime.process.WorkItemHandler> handlers) {
        this(app.config().process());
        this.app = app;
        org.kie.api.runtime.process.WorkItemManager workItemManager = services.getWorkItemManager();
        for (WorkItemHandler wih : handlers) {
            workItemManager.registerWorkItemHandler(wih.getClass().getCanonicalName(), wih);
        }
        this.activate();
}
thus transforming the code as such:
    @javax.inject.Inject()
    public TravellersProcess(
        org.kie.kogito.app.Application app, 
        // java.util.Collection in the case of Spring
        javax.enterprise.inject.Instance<org.kie.api.runtime.process.WorkItemHandler> handlers) {
        super(app.config().process(), handlers);
    }
as you can see, this way we trim down the generated code considerably, we get a much more meaningful and simpler template


Now, for the @Lazy annotation, first of all I would like to know what's causing the issue, and rather try to solve the issue at its root if possible; IIRC Application gets injected ApplicationProcesses, which contains all of the available processes; this in a CDI/Spring context is not a dependency of this class; however, this could be still cyclic; to resolve the cycle, it may be just enough to annotate the class kogito-codegen/src/main/resources/class-templates/SpringProcessContainerTemplate.javawith @Lazy


if there is not way to break the cycle, then I'd rather annotate the constructor rather than the single parameters


hope this answers all of your questions

